 the Rishis asked &quot;How?&quot;. \n\n\nIn Yoga the idea is to restrain th=\r\ne inputs from the sense-organs and eventually discover the changeless state=\r\n. In Tantra the idea is to divinize the inputs from the sense-organs and ev=\r\nentually spiritualize yourself, transform the limited personality into a di=\r\nvine one and live in this world. End results of both the paths are practica=\r\nlly same, but the perspectives and paradigms are different.=C2=A0\n\nIt is ve=\r\nry difficult to meet a genuine Bhairavi, even in this age when society has =\r\nbecome relatively &#39;free&#39; \n\nwith respect to women expressing themselves and =\r\nsexuality in general. What the beat generation and hippie movement and wome=\r\nn&#39;s-lib movements are doing today, the Tantras had done it ages ago but on =\r\na firm plank of practical spirituality. The term Bhairavi refers to a form =\r\nof the Divine Feminine energy (Aadya Shakti), a Goddess in her own rights, =\r\nwhose energy, if it were to possess a woman, would make her so fearless and=\r\n rooted into herself that she would not mind transgressing and breaking soc=\r\nial mores and thus evoke either fear or awe or a sense of disowning from a =\r\nsociety conditioned over centuries to believe in fixed ideas of spiritualit=\r\ny and moral behavior. On a practical side, every genuine Bhairavi always, a=\r\nlways looks a good decade or two younger than their physical age, and tend =\r\nto have some very distinct and remarkable facial features. In Vaishnava Tan=\r\ntras, which have become extinct now, Krishna was considered a MahaBhairava =\r\nand Radha was His\n Bhairavi. \n\nAnyway, if you are meant to meet one, you wi=\r\nll I am sure. \n\n&lt;&lt;it&#39;s not a perfect homam technique wise, but I try and pu=\r\nt a bit of \nheart in it. And if I can&#39;t find any heart, I blame Durga for n=\r\not giving\n me any! She gets a lot of abuse from me I&#39;m afraid, but as she m=\r\nade me,\n it&#39;s her own fault). &gt