y spiritualize yourself, transfor=\r\nm the limited personality into a divine one and live in this\n world. End re=\r\nsults of both the paths are practically same, but the perspectives and para=\r\ndigms are different.&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;It is very difficult to=\r\n meet a genuine Bhairavi, even in this age when society has become relative=\r\nly &#39;free&#39; &lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;with respect to women expressing themselves and se=\r\nxuality in general. What the beat generation and hippie movement and women&#39;=\r\ns-lib movements are doing today, the Tantras had done it ages ago but on a =\r\nfirm plank of practical spirituality. The term Bhairavi refers to a form of=\r\n the Divine Feminine energy (Aadya Shakti), a Goddess in her own rights, wh=\r\nose energy, if it were to possess a woman, would make her so fearless and r=\r\nooted into herself that she would not mind transgressing and breaking socia=\r\nl mores and thus evoke either fear or awe or a sense of disowning from a so=\r\nciety conditioned over centuries to believe in fixed ideas of spirituality =\r\nand moral behavior. On a practical side, every genuine\n Bhairavi always, al=\r\nways looks a good decade or two younger than their physical age, and tend t=\r\no have some very distinct and remarkable facial features. In Vaishnava Tant=\r\nras, which have become extinct now, Krishna was considered a MahaBhairava a=\r\nnd Radha was His Bhairavi. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Anyway, if you are meant to meet one, yo=\r\nu will I am sure. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;&lt;it&#39;s not a perfect homam technique wise, =\r\nbut I try and put a bit of \nheart in it. And if I can&#39;t find any heart, I b=\r\nlame Durga for not giving\n me any! She gets a lot of abuse from me I&#39;m afra=\r\nid, but as she made me,\n it&#39;s her own fault). &gt;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Homas with he=\r\nart are a good thing. Eventually it strengthens the inner voice and helps o=\r\nne to